description:
English translation of the Japanese manga Sengoku Nights.

From the creators of Diabolo When evil is resurrected, it's up to one boy to give them hell.At first glance, Masayoshi Kurozuka is an ordinary high school kid...until the day he discovers that he is the reincarnation of an evil woman named Oni-hime, who sold her soul to the devil during Japan's warring period. Masayoshi must come to grips with his gruesome destiny--while fighting off legions of ghosts, the remnants of men killed by Oni-hime! From the creators of TOKYOPOP's Diabolo comes a sinister and compelling horror story taken from traditional Japanese mythological roots.
name: Sengoku Nights

description:
Sergeant Keroro (aka Sgt Frog), is captain of the Special Advance Team for Space Invasion, for planet 58 in the Gamma Storm Cloud System.

He is sent on a mission to Pokopen (aka Earth) to collect information for his planet's Invasion Force!

But all does not go to plan when he crash-lands his spacecraft and is forced to take shelter in a nearby house. The children of said house, Fuyuki and Natsume, take him in as a friend but when the frogs of planet 58 find that Keroro has blown his cover, he is left to fend for himself on this hostile planet....

But it he the only Invasion Agent to have failed his quest on Pokopen...?

Collected Editions

  • Sgt. Frog vol. 1 (vol. 1-3)

description: Battle Stories was a K-ration quality war series set in Korea, published in the early 1950s by Fawcett, who was clearly running out of creative steam by that point. Stories like “You’ll Never Be Twenty,” “Platoon Forward” and “Land-Lubber” offer war combat action in all its violence and gritty detail, with stock characters falling on grenades to save the rest of the squadron, grizzled veterans warning the fresh-faced recruits about the dangers ahead, and courageous soldiers overmatched by scores of enemy troops finding a way back home against all odds. The ugly stories are matched with ugly, claustrophobic artwork and a generally malevolent editorial tone.
name: Battle Stories

description:
Bill Boyd starred as himself in this spin-off title of his most famous alter ego Hopalong Cassidy. To differentiate this from the Hoppy title, Boyd was given a different horse (Midnite instead of Topper). Apparently, issuing a western comic book under Hoppy’s real name wasn’t nearly as successful as the parent title as this title only lasted about two years, as compared to Hopalong’s 16-year reign between two different publishers (Fawcett and DC). However, most of the adventures were typical cowboy stuff, so for fans of the genre, these are a must.

— Mark Arnold
name: Bill Boyd Western

issues.name: The Lost City of the Sun

description:
Billy the Kid is a cowboy hat-wearing, gun-toting goat. His friend Oscar happens to be an ostrich, and the sheriff of the town. Together they solve mysteries, throw bad guys in the slammer, and keep the wild west safe for all the animals.

As an example of the series, in “A Strangle Hold,” when a famous murder mystery writer visits the town and his host turns up dead, it’s up to Billy and Oscar to determine the real culprit.

This series also contains short stories highlighting characters such as Willie the Worm, Benny Beaver, Fuzzy Bear, and others also featured in Fawcett’s Funny Animals.
name: Billy the Kid and Oscar

description: Wartime Fawcett Comics hero Spy Smasher was popular enough in his heyday to rate his own movie serial, but civilian life wasn’t as kind. Spy Smasher retired in Whiz Comics #76 to take up domestic duties as a hardboiled, private eye, styled Crime Smasher. He was given his own title in 1948 with Crime Smasher featured on the cover machine-gunning a fleeing crook. Despite several tales of two-fisted detective action, sleazy crooks, desperate women, and above-average illustration from the Fawcett staff, Crime Smasher didn’t make it past the first issue.
name: Crime Smasher

description:
One shot Australian comic published in black & white between full color cardboard covers tells the story of mad scientist Doctor Son-Yo and his various diabolical inventions, including shrink and growth rays, a magnetic beam for snaring ships, robot servants, and a ray that “develops to an abnormal degree the good or bad in a human mind.”

Into this two man, an Australian and a New Zealander, wash ashore on a raft observing what he is doing, part of which involves him using his magnetic beam to capture and shrink a German battleship for his own amusement.

However other than turning a captured Australian “public benefactor” into a “human vulture” with his evil / good ray his long range plans are never revealed before his robot servants revolt destroying the Doctor and his devices.
name: Island of Amazement!
